exten => minivm,1,answer exten => minivm,n,wait(0.5) ; Wait for Voip channels to settle exten => minivm,n,set(account=oej@example.com) exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Greet -------------) exten => minivm,n,minivmgreet(${account}) exten => minivm,n,verbose(1,-- MINIVM_GREET_STATUS = ${MINIVM_GREET_STATUS} ) exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Record -------------) exten => minivm,n,minivmRecord(${account},b) exten => minivm,n,goto(minivmcleanup,1)

The provided code snippet appears to be an Asterisk dialplan configuration for a mini voicemail (minivm) system. Here's a breakdown of what each line does:

  1. exten => minivm,1,answer: This line answers the incoming call.

  2. exten => minivm,n,wait(0.5): This line introduces a half-second wait to allow VoIP channels to settle before proceeding.

  3. exten => minivm,n,set(account=oej@example.com): This line sets a variable account to the email address oej@example.com, which likely represents the voicemail account being accessed.

  4. exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Greet -------------): This line is a no-operation command that serves as a comment or marker in the dialplan for clarity.

  5. exten => minivm,n,minivmgreet(${account}): This line calls a custom application or function minivmgreet with the account variable, which presumably plays a greeting message for the voicemail account.

  6. exten => minivm,n,verbose(1,-- MINIVM_GREET_STATUS = ${MINIVM_GREET_STATUS} ): This line logs the status of the greeting playback to the Asterisk console, which can be useful for debugging.

  7. exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Record -------------): Another no-operation command that serves as a comment or marker for the recording section.

  8. exten => minivm,n,minivmRecord(${account},b): This line calls another custom application or function minivmRecord, which likely handles the recording of a voicemail message for the specified account. The b parameter may indicate a specific type of recording or behavior.

  9. exten => minivm,n,goto(minivmcleanup,1): This line directs the flow to another context or extension labeled minivmcleanup, starting at priority 1, which likely handles cleanup tasks after the voicemail recording is complete.

Summary

This dialplan is designed to handle voicemail greetings and recordings for a specific account in an Asterisk-based telephony system. It includes waiting for the VoIP channels to settle, playing a greeting, logging the status, recording a message, and then cleaning up afterward. If you have any specific questions or need further modifications, feel free to ask!

OK, how to configure the miniwm

Configuring a mini voicemail (minivm) system in Asterisk involves several steps, including setting up the dialplan, configuring voicemail settings, and ensuring that the necessary modules are loaded. Below is a general guide to help you configure a mini voicemail system in Asterisk:

Step 1: Install Asterisk

Make sure you have Asterisk installed on your server. You can download it from the Asterisk website.

Step 2: Configure Voicemail

  1. Edit the Voicemail Configuration File: Open the voicemail.conf file, usually located in /etc/asterisk/.

    bash
    nano /etc/asterisk/voicemail.conf

    Add a voicemail context for your users. For example:

    ini
    [default]
1000 => 1234,User One,user1@example.com
1001 => 1234,User Two,user2@example.com

    In this example, two users are configured with their respective voicemail boxes.

  2. Set Up Mailbox Directory: Ensure that the mailbox directory exists. By default, it is usually located at /var/spool/asterisk/voicemail/default/. You may need to create it if it doesn't exist.

    bash
    mkdir -p /var/spool/asterisk/voicemail/default/1000
mkdir -p /var/spool/asterisk/voicemail/default/1001

Step 3: Configure the Dialplan

  1. Edit the Dialplan Configuration File: Open the extensions.conf file, usually located in /etc/asterisk/.

    bash
    nano /etc/asterisk/extensions.conf

    Add the mini voicemail context. Here’s an example based on your initial code:

    ini
    [minivm]
exten => minivm,1,answer
exten => minivm,n,wait(0.5)
exten => minivm,n,set(account=oej@example.com)
exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Greet  -------------)
exten => minivm,n,minivmgreet(${account})
exten => minivm,n,verbose(1,-- MINIVM_GREET_STATUS = ${MINIVM_GREET_STATUS} )
exten => minivm,n,noop(------------------------------------------- Minivm Record  -------------)
exten => minivm,n,minivmRecord(${account},b)
exten => minivm,n,goto(minivmcleanup,1)

[minivmcleanup]
exten => 1,1,noop(Cleaning up after voicemail)
exten => 1,n,hangup()

Step 4: Create Custom Applications (if needed)

If minivmgreet and minivmRecord are custom applications, you will need to implement them. This typically involves writing a custom Asterisk module in C or using AGI (Asterisk Gateway Interface) scripts.

Step 5: Reload Asterisk Configuration

After making changes to the configuration files, reload the Asterisk configuration to apply the changes:

bash
asterisk -rx "reload"

Step 6: Test the Configuration

Make a call to the extension that triggers the mini voicemail system and ensure that the greeting plays and that you can record messages.

Additional Considerations

  • Permissions: Ensure that the Asterisk user has the necessary permissions to read/write to the voicemail directories.
  • Audio Files: Make sure that the audio files for greetings are in the correct format (usually WAV or GSM) and are placed in the appropriate directories.
  • Logging: Check the Asterisk logs for any errors or issues during testing. Logs are typically found in /var/log/asterisk/.

Conclusion

This guide provides a basic setup for a mini voicemail system in Asterisk. Depending on your specific requirements, you may need to customize the dialplan further or implement additional features. If you have any specific questions or need help with a particular aspect, feel free to ask!

for what's the user1@example.com?

In the context of the Asterisk voicemail configuration, user1@example.com is an email address associated with a specific voicemail user (in this case, "User One"). This email address serves a couple of purposes:

  1. Notification: When a voicemail is left for the user, Asterisk can be configured to send an email notification to this address. The notification typically includes details about the voicemail, such as the caller's number, the time of the call, and sometimes even an audio file of the voicemail message itself as an attachment.

  2. Voicemail Retrieval: Some configurations allow users to retrieve their voicemail messages via email. This can be done by sending the voicemail audio files to the user's email address, allowing them to listen to their messages from their email client.

Example Configuration

In the voicemail.conf file, the line:

ini
1000 => 1234,User One,user1@example.com

indicates that:

  • 1000: This is the mailbox number for User One.
  • 1234: This is the password that User One will use to access their voicemail.
  • User One: This is the display name for the user.
  • user1@example.com: This is the email address where notifications will be sent.

Customization

You can customize the email address to match the actual email addresses of your users. If you have multiple users, each user can have their own unique email address for notifications.

Summary

In summary, user1@example.com is used for sending voicemail notifications and potentially for retrieving voicemail messages via email. It helps users stay informed about their voicemails without needing to check their voicemail box directly.

i have the vadisp927@gmail.com only, can i use it for minivm?

Yes, you can use your email address vadisp927@gmail.com for the mini voicemail (minivm) configuration in Asterisk. You would simply replace the email address in the voicemail.conf file with your own. Here’s how you can do it:

Step 1: Edit the Voicemail Configuration

Open the voicemail.conf file, usually located in /etc/asterisk/.

bash
nano /etc/asterisk/voicemail.conf

Step 2: Update the User Configuration

Modify the entry for the user to include your email address. For example:

ini
[default]
1000 => 1234,User One,vadisp927@gmail.com

In this example:

  • 1000: This is the mailbox number for User One.
  • 1234: This is the password that User One will use to access their voicemail.
  • User One: This is the display name for the user.
  • vadisp927@gmail.com: This is the email address where voicemail notifications will be sent.

Step 3: Save and Exit

After making the changes, save the file and exit the text editor.

Step 4: Reload Asterisk Configuration

To apply the changes, reload the Asterisk configuration:

bash
asterisk -rx "reload"

Step 5: Test the Configuration

Make a call to the extension that triggers the mini voicemail system and leave a message. Check your email (vadisp927@gmail.com) to see if you receive a notification about the voicemail.

Additional Considerations

  • Email Configuration: Ensure that your Asterisk server is configured to send emails. This may involve setting up an SMTP server or using an external email service. You may need to configure the mail command or use a tool like msmtp or sendmail to handle outgoing emails.
  • Spam Filters: Check your spam or junk folder if you do not see the email notifications in your inbox.

By following these steps, you can successfully use your email address for the mini voicemail system in Asterisk. If you have any further questions or need assistance with specific configurations, feel free to ask!

OK, msmtp for archlinux,please

To set up msmtp on Arch Linux for sending emails from your Asterisk server, follow these steps:

Step 1: Install msmtp

First, you need to install msmtp. You can do this using the package manager pacman.

bash
sudo pacman -S msmtp

Step 2: Configure msmtp

Next, you need to create a configuration file for msmtp. This file will contain the settings for your email account.

  1. Create the Configuration File: Create a file named .msmtprc in your home directory:

    bash
    nano ~/.msmtprc

  2. Add Configuration Settings: Add the following configuration to the file, replacing the placeholders with your actual email account details:

    ini
    # Set default values for all accounts
defaults
auth           on
tls            on
tls_trust_file /etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt
logfile        ~/.msmtp.log

# Gmail account
account        gmail
host           smtp.gmail.com
port           587
from           vadisp927@gmail.com
user           vadisp927@gmail.com
password       your_gmail_app_password

# Set a default account
account default : gmail

    Note:

    • Replace your_gmail_app_password with an app password generated from your Google account. If you have 2-Step Verification enabled, you will need to create an app password specifically for this purpose. You can do this in your Google Account settings under "Security" > "App passwords."
    • If you do not have 2-Step Verification enabled, you may need to allow "Less secure apps" in your Google account settings, but this is not recommended for security reasons.

  3. Set Permissions: Set the correct permissions for the .msmtprc file to ensure that it is not readable by others:

    bash
    chmod 600 ~/.msmtprc

Step 3: Test msmtp

You can test your msmtp configuration by sending a test email from the command line:

bash
echo "Test email body" | msmtp vadisp927@gmail.com

Check your inbox to see if you received the email.

Step 4: Configure Asterisk to Use msmtp

Now that msmtp is set up, you need to configure Asterisk to use it for sending voicemail notifications.

  1. Edit the Asterisk Voicemail Configuration: Open the voicemail.conf file:

    bash
    nano /etc/asterisk/voicemail.conf

    Ensure that the email address is set correctly for the user.

  2. Edit the Asterisk Email Configuration: Open the voicemail.conf file and ensure that the following line is present:

    ini
    ; Email settings
email = yes

  3. Set Up the Mail Command: Asterisk uses the mail command to send emails. You can create a simple script to use msmtp for sending emails. Create a script named sendmail.sh:

    bash
    sudo nano /usr/local/bin/sendmail.sh

    Add the following content to the script:

    bash
    #!/bin/bash
/usr/bin/msmtp --from=default -t "$@"

    Make the script executable:

    bash
    sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/sendmail.sh

  4. Configure Asterisk to Use the Script: Open the extensions.conf file:

    bash
    nano /etc/asterisk/extensions.conf

    In the voicemail context, you can specify the sendmail command to use your script:

    ini
    exten => 1000,n,Set(EMAIL=vadisp927@gmail.com)
exten => 1000,n,System(/usr/local/bin/sendmail.sh "${EMAIL}" < /var/spool/asterisk/voicemail/default/1000/INBOX/your_voicemail_file)

Step 5: Reload Asterisk Configuration

After making all the changes, reload the Asterisk configuration:

bash
asterisk -rx "reload"

Conclusion

You should now have msmtp configured on your Arch Linux system to send emails, and Asterisk should be set up to use it for sending voicemail notifications. Test the voicemail system to ensure that you receive emails when voicemails are left. If you encounter any issues or have further questions, feel free to ask!

gmail don't allow to use. What's another variant the email provider for it?

If Gmail is not an option for sending emails from your Asterisk server, there are several other email providers you can consider. Here are a few popular alternatives that support SMTP and can be used with msmtp:

1. ProtonMail

ProtonMail offers a secure email service, but it requires a paid plan for SMTP access. If you choose this option, you will need to set up ProtonMail Bridge, which allows you to use ProtonMail with email clients.

2. Zoho Mail

Zoho Mail provides a free tier with SMTP access. You can sign up for a Zoho Mail account and use their SMTP server.

  • SMTP Server: smtp.zoho.com
  • Port: 587 (TLS)
  • Username: Your Zoho email address
  • Password: Your Zoho password

3. Outlook.com (Microsoft)

Outlook.com provides SMTP access and can be used for sending emails.

  • SMTP Server: smtp.office365.com
  • Port: 587 (TLS)
  • Username: Your Outlook email address
  • Password: Your Outlook password

4. Sendinblue

Sendinblue offers a free tier with SMTP access, but it has a daily sending limit. You can sign up for an account and use their SMTP server.

  • SMTP Server: smtp.sendinblue.com
  • Port: 587 (TLS)
  • Username: Your Sendinblue email address
  • Password: Your Sendinblue password

5. Mailgun

Mailgun is a transactional email service that offers a free tier with a limited number of emails per month. You can use it for sending emails programmatically.

  • SMTP Server: smtp.mailgun.org
  • Port: 587 (TLS)
  • Username: Your Mailgun SMTP username
  • Password: Your Mailgun SMTP password

6. Yahoo Mail

Yahoo Mail also provides SMTP access, but you may need to generate an app password if you have two-step verification enabled.

  • SMTP Server: smtp.mail.yahoo.com
  • Port: 587 (TLS)
  • Username: Your Yahoo email address
  • Password: Your Yahoo password or app password

Example Configuration for Zoho Mail

If you decide to use Zoho Mail, here’s how you would configure msmtp:

  1. Edit the .msmtprc File: Open or create the .msmtprc file in your home directory:

    bash
    nano ~/.msmtprc

  2. Add the Zoho Mail Configuration: Replace the existing configuration with the following:

    ini
    defaults
auth           on
tls            on
tls_trust_file /etc/ssl/certs/ca-certificates.crt
logfile        ~/.msmtp.log

account        zoho
host           smtp.zoho.com
port           587
from           your_zoho_email@zoho.com
user           your_zoho_email@zoho.com
password       your_zoho_password

account default : zoho

  3. Set Permissions: Ensure the permissions are set correctly:

    bash
    chmod 600 ~/.msmtprc

  4. Test the Configuration: Test sending an email using msmtp:

    bash
    echo "Test email body" | msmtp your_zoho_email@zoho.com

Conclusion

Choose an email provider that fits your needs and follow the steps to configure msmtp accordingly. Each provider will have its own settings, so make sure to refer to their documentation for any specific requirements. If you have any further questions or need assistance with a specific provider, feel free to ask!
